    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start, but some critics argue that this kind of judicial interpretation is actually undemocratic because it allows judges to create rights that aren't written in the Constitution. How would you address that argument in my lesson? I want to make sure the students understand why this method is so important despite those criticisms.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To address this, you can explain that substantive due process functions as a necessary check on majoritarian tyranny, ensuring that the government cannot violate fundamental rights simply because a popular vote supports an infringement. While critics rightly point out the tension between judicial power and democracy, proponents argue that this framework prevents the \"tyranny of the majority\" and validates the principle that certain individual liberties transcend popular opinion. Ultimately, it highlights the Constitution's living nature, requiring courts to interpret rights dynamically rather than locking them into 19th-century assumptions. This highlights the ongoing democratic debate about who has the authority to define the bounds of governmental power.",
      "source": "target",
